  "prompt": "What are some examples of cardiac muscles?",
  "response": "Cardiac muscle refers to the specialized muscle tissue that makes up the heart. Unlike skeletal muscle, cardiac muscle is involuntary and striated, meaning it has a banded appearance. The primary example of cardiac muscle is the myocardium, which is the thick middle layer of the heart wall that is responsible for contracting and pumping blood throughout the body. \n\nCardiac muscle is unique in that it consists of individual muscle cells, or cardiomyocytes, that are interconnected by intercalated discs. These discs enable synchronized contraction and communication between the cells. Additionally, features of cardiac muscle include:\n\n1. **Atria and Ventricles**: The myocardium forms the walls of the heart's four chambers\u2014the left atrium, right atrium, left ventricle, and right ventricle.\n\n2. **Sinoatrial Node (SA Node)**: While not muscle tissue itself, the cells in the SA node (the heart's natural pacemaker) are modified cardiac muscle cells that generate electrical impulses.\n\n3. **Purkinje Fibers**: Specialized fibers that are part of the conduction system of the heart and help transmit signals for heart contraction.\n\nOverall, cardiac muscle is specifically related to the heart, and all regions of the heart that contract (i.e., the atria and ventricles) are composed of this type of muscle tissue.",
